The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                            Tuesday , November 10 , 2009                                                                                                                                                                                            The City Diary
                The family members of a 28-year-old man, who died while undergoing treatment at a drug rehabilitation centre in Behala on Sunday night, have lodged a police complaint accusing the centre of negligence.																																																								  Family members took Sanjib De from the centre to Ramakrishna Mission Seva Pratishthan where he was declared dead. According to Des relatives, the authorities at the centre said the youth, a resident of Kasba, didnt receive medical attention since the centres officials were unable to contact any local doctor.  Des cousin said they had received a call from the centre and reached there to find the youth lying unconscious on the floor. More than a dozen patients were undergoing treatment at the centre, he added.																																																								  The home authorities refused comment. The police have started an unnatural death case and sent the body for post-mortem. A family member said De had been re-admitted to the centre on November 2 after he had tried to commit suicide at his residence the day before.     An 11-year-old girl, suffering from malaria, died at Calcutta Medical College and Hospital on Monday. Aiswarya Datta, a resident of the College Street area, was admitted to the hospital on Sunday. The civic health department refused to record it as a case of malarial death as the death certificate mentioned plasmodium vivax, which does not cause malignant malaria.     The indefinite strike called by taxi unions on November 12 has been deferred till December 2. The decision was taken after the taxi unions met transport minister Ranjit Kundu on Monday. Bimal Guha of Bengal Taxi Association said they wanted to exert pressure on Hindustan Motors to speed up the supply of Ambassadors.     A 22-year-old employee of a restaurant at Calcutta airport allegedly committed suicide late on Sunday. Police said Babu Patra consumed caustic soda and jumped off the roof of the building that houses the CISF office. The Joka resident was taken to RG Kar hospital, where he was declared dead.    One person died and two were injured in separate accidents in the city on Monday. Nitai Chandra Das, 70, died after an unidentified vehicle knocked him down on Mayo Road at 2.35pm. He was taken to SSKM Hospital, where he succumbed to his injuries. Earlier in the day, Pratyush Agarwal, 18, was seriously injured in the leg when an unidentified vehicle hit his motorcycle near Park Clinic on AJC Bose Road. He was taken to Belle Vue Clinic. Pillion rider Kriti Agarwal, 19, was discharged after treatment.    Two persons were arrested and three country-made pipeguns, five bottle bombs, a few crude bombs and 4kg ganja seized from their car on Monday afternoon in the Nayapatti area of Salt Lake. Police said the car was intercepted after a patrol van spotted different number plates on its front and back. Three members of the gang escaped.     Three men were arrested for trying to steal a car by threatening the driver with a sharp weapon on the EM Bypass late on Sunday. Police said four men boarded Nikhilesh Singhs vehicle near Ruby General Hospital. The car was intercepted by cops near the Beleghata Main Road-EM Bypass crossing after Singh shouted for help near a police kiosk. The fourth member of the gang fled.     Members of the 1986 batch of St Xaviers Collegiate School, Calcutta, who have collected around Rs 2 crore to be distributed among their teachers, have appealed to their batchmates who are willing to contribute to contact jishnu.sengrey.com.             
